.TH "CMAKE-CXXMODULES" "7" "Jun 11, 2026" "4.4.0" "CMake"
.SH NAME
cmake-cxxmodules \- CMake C++ Modules Support Reference
.sp
Added in version 3.28.

.sp
C++ 20 introduced the concept of \(dqmodules\(dq to the
language.  The design requires build systems to order
compilations to satisfy \fBimport\fP statements reliably.  CMake\(aqs
implementation asks the compiler to scan source files for module dependencies
during the build, collates scanning results to infer ordering constraints, and
tells the build tool how to dynamically update the
build graph.
.SH COMPILATION STRATEGY
.sp
With C++ modules, compiling a set of C++ sources is no longer
embarrassingly parallel\&.  That is, any given source may require the
compilation of another source file first in order to provide a
\(dqBMI\(dq (or
\(dqCMI\(dq) that C++ compilers use to satisfy
\fBimport\fP statements in other sources.  With included headers, sources could
share their declarations so that any consumers could compile independently.
With modules, the compiler now generates BMI files during compilation
based on the contents of the source file and its \fBexport\fP statements.  This
means that, to ensure a correct build without having to regenerate the build
graph (by running configure and generate steps) for every source change, the
correct ordering must be determined from the source files during the build
phase.
.sp
Build systems must be able to order these compilations
within the build graph.  There are multiple strategies that are suitable for
this, but each has advantages and disadvantages.  CMake uses a \(dqscanning\(dq step
strategy, which is the most visible modules\-related change for CMake users in
the context of the build.  CMake provides multiple ways to control the
scanning behavior of source files.
.SH SCANNING CONTROL
.sp
Whether or not sources get scanned for C++ module usage is dependent on the
following queries.  The first query that provides a decision of whether to
scan or not is used.
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
If the source file belongs to a file set of type \fBCXX_MODULES\fP, it will
be scanned.
.IP \(bu 2
If the target does not use at least C++ 20, it will not be scanned.
.IP \(bu 2
If the source file is not the language \fBCXX\fP, it will not be scanned.
.IP \(bu 2
If the source file belongs to a file set that is not of type \fBCXX_MODULES\fP,
and the \fBCXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES\fP \%<#\:prop_fs:CXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES> file set property is set, its
value will be used.
.IP \(bu 2
If the \fBCXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES\fP \%<#\:prop_sf:CXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES> source file property is set in the
target\(aqs directory, its value will be used.
.IP \(bu 2
If the \fBCXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:CXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES> target property is set, its value
will be used.  Set the \fBCMAKE_CXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES\fP \%<#\:variable:CMAKE_CXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES> variable
to initialize this property on all targets as they are created.
.IP \(bu 2
Otherwise, the source file will be scanned if the compiler and generator
support scanning.  See policy \fBCMP0155\fP \%<#\:policy:CMP0155>\&.
.UNINDENT
.sp
Note that any scanned source will be excluded from any unity build (see
\fBUNITY_BUILD\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:UNITY_BUILD>) because module\-related statements can only happen at
one place within a C++ translation unit.
.SH COMPILER SUPPORT
.sp
The list of compilers for which CMake supports scanning sources for C++
modules includes:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
MSVC toolset 14.34 and newer (provided with Visual Studio 17.4 and newer)
.IP \(bu 2
LLVM/Clang 16.0 and newer
.sp
Added in version 4.4: \fBclang\-cl\fP version 19.1 and newer

.IP \(bu 2
GCC 14 and newer
.UNINDENT
.SH IMPORT STD SUPPORT
.sp
Support for \fBimport std\fP is limited to the following toolchain and standard
library combinations:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
Clang 18.1.2 and newer with standard library \fBlibc++\fP or \fBlibstdc++\fP
.IP \(bu 2
MSVC toolset 14.36 and newer (provided with Visual Studio 17.6 and newer)
.IP \(bu 2
GCC 15 and newer
.sp
\fBNote:\fP
.INDENT 2.0
.INDENT 3.5
Ubuntu prior to 26.04 ships broken \fBlibstdc++.modules.json\fP files.
See Ubuntu issue 2141579 \%<https://\:bugs\:.launchpad\:.net/\:ubuntu/\:+source/\:gcc-15/\:+bug/\:2141579>\&.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The \fBCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_IMPORT_STD\fP \%<#\:variable:CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_IMPORT_STD> variable lists standard levels
which have support for \fBimport std\fP in the active C++ toolchain.
.sp
Additionally, only the Ninja Generators \%<#\:ninja-generators> currently support
\fBimport std\fP at this time because Visual Studio Generators \%<#\:visual-studio-generators> do not
support building BMIs for \fBIMPORTED\fP targets.
.sp
\fBNote:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
This support is provided only when experimental support for
\fBimport std\fP has been enabled by the
\fBCMAKE_EXPERIMENTAL_CXX_IMPORT_STD\fP gate.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SH GENERATOR SUPPORT
.sp
The list of generators which support scanning sources for C++ modules
includes:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBNinja\fP \%<#\:generator:Ninja>
.IP \(bu 2
\fBNinja Multi\-Config\fP \%<#\:generator:Ninja Multi-Config>
.IP \(bu 2
\fBVisual Studio 17 2022\fP \%<#\:generator:Visual Studio 17 2022>
.IP \(bu 2
\fBVisual Studio 18 2026\fP \%<#\:generator:Visual Studio 18 2026>
.UNINDENT
.sp
Note that the Ninja Generators \%<#\:ninja-generators> require \fBninja\fP 1.11 or newer.
.SS Limitations
.sp
There are a number of known limitations of the current C++ module support in
CMake.  Known limitations or bugs in compilers are not listed here, as these
can change over time.
.sp
For all generators:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
Header units are not supported.
.UNINDENT
.sp
For the Visual Studio Generators \%<#\:visual-studio-generators>:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
Only Visual Studio 2022 and MSVC toolsets 14.34 (Visual Studio
17.4) and newer are supported.
.IP \(bu 2
Exporting or installing BMI or module information is not supported.
.IP \(bu 2
Compiling BMIs from \fBIMPORTED\fP targets with C++ modules
(including \fBimport std\fP) is not supported.
.IP \(bu 2
Use of modules provided by \fBPRIVATE\fP sources from \fBPUBLIC\fP module
sources is not diagnosed.
.UNINDENT
.sp
Separately, as a design choice, CMake does not express configuration\-agnostic
module maps for imported targets. The \fBIMPORTED_CXX_MODULES_<CONFIG>\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:IMPORTED_CXX_MODULES_<CONFIG>>
target property is always tied to a specific configuration. This can lead to
some friction when importing/exporting targets from/to configuration\-unaware
build systems. Future work will alleviate this restriction.
.SH USAGE
.SS Troubleshooting CMake
.sp
This section aims to answer common questions about CMake\(aqs implementation and
to help diagnose or explain errors in CMake\(aqs C++ modules support.
.SS File Extension Support
.sp
CMake imposes no requirements upon file extensions for modules of any unit
type.  While there are preferences that differ between toolchains (e.g.,
\fB\&.ixx\fP on MSVC and \fB\&.cppm\fP on Clang), there is no universally agreed\-upon
extension.  As such, CMake only requires that the file be recognized as a
\fBCXX\fP\-language source file.  By default, any recognized extension will
suffice, but the \fBLANGUAGE\fP \%<#\:prop_sf:LANGUAGE> property may be used with any other
extension as well.
.SS File Name Requirements
.sp
The name of a module has no relation to the name or path of the file in which
its declaration resides.  The C++ standard has no requirements here and
neither does CMake.  However, it may be useful to have some pattern in use
within a project for easier navigation within environments that lack IDE\-like
\(dqfind symbol\(dq functionality (e.g., on code review platforms).
.SS Scanning Without Modules
.sp
A common problem for projects that have not yet adopted modules is unnecessary
scanning of sources.  This typically happens when a C++20 project becomes
aware of CMake 3.28, or a 3.28\-aware project starts using C++20.  Either case
ends up setting \fBCMP0155\fP \%<#\:policy:CMP0155> to \fBNEW\fP, which enables scanning of C++
sources with C++20 or newer by default.  The easiest way for projects to turn
this off is to add:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
set(CMAKE_CXX_SCAN_FOR_MODULES 0)
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
near the top of their top\-level \fBCMakeLists.txt\fP file.  Note that it should
\fBnot\fP be in the cache, as it may otherwise affect projects using it via
\fBFetchContent\fP\&.  Attention should also be paid to vendored projects which
may want to enable scanning for their own sources, as this would change the
default for them as well.
.SS Debugging Module Builds
.sp
This section aims to help diagnose or explain common errors that may arise on
the build side of CMake\(aqs C++ modules support.
.SS Import Cycles
.sp
The C++ standard does not allow for cycles in the \fBimport\fP graph of a
translation unit; therefore, CMake does not either.  Currently, CMake
will leave it to the build tool to detect this based on the
dynamic dependencies used to order module compilations.
CMake Issue 26119 \%<https://\:gitlab\:.kitware\:.com/\:cmake/\:cmake/\:-/\:issues/\:26119> tracks the desire to improve the user experience in this
case.
.SS Internal Module Partition Extension
.sp
When the implementation of building C++ modules was first investigated, it
appeared as though there existed a type of translation unit that
represented the intersection of a partition unit and an
implementation unit\&.  Initial CMake designs included specific support
for these translation units; however, after a closer reading of the standard,
these did not actually exist.  These units would have had \fBmodule M:part;\fP
as their module declaration statement.  The problem is that this is also the
exact syntax also used for declaring module partitions that do not contribute
to the external interface of the primary module.  Only MSVC supports this
distinction.  Other compilers do not and will treat such files as an
internal partition unit and CMake will raise an error that a
module\-providing C++ source must be in a \fBFILE_SET\fP of type \fBCXX_MODULES\fP\&.
.sp
The fix is to not use the extension, as it provides no further expressivity
over not using the extension.  All implementation unit source files
should instead only use \fBmodule M;\fP as their module declaration statement
regardless of what partition the defined entities are declared within.  As an
example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
// module\-interface.cpp
export module M;
export int foo();

// module\-impl.cpp
module M:part; // module M:part; looks like an internal partition
int foo() { return 42; }
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Instead use explicit interface/implementation separation:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
// module\-interface.cpp
export module M;
export int foo();

// module\-impl.cpp
module M;
int foo() { return 42; }
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Module Visibility
.sp
CMake enforces module visibility between and within targets.  This
essentially means that a module (say, \fBI\fP) provided from a \fBPRIVATE\fP
\fBFILE_SET\fP on a target \fBT\fP may not be imported by:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
other targets depending on \fBT\fP; or
.IP \(bu 2
modules provided from a \fBPUBLIC\fP \fBFILE_SET\fP on target \fBT\fP itself.
.UNINDENT
.sp
This is because, in general, all imported entities from a module must also be
importable by all potential importers of that module.  Even if module \fBI\fP is
only used within parts of a module without the \fBexport\fP keyword, it may
affect things within it in such a way that consumers of the module need to be
able to transitively \fBimport\fP it to work correctly.  As CMake uses the
module visibility to determine whether to install module interface
units, a \fBPRIVATE\fP module interface unit will not
be installed, meaning that usage of any installed module which imports \fBI\fP
would not work.
.sp
Instead, import \fBPRIVATE\fP C++ modules only from within an
implementation unit, as these are not exposed to consumers of any
module.
.SH DESIGN
.sp
The design of CMake\(aqs C++ module support makes a number of trade\-offs compared
to other designs.  First, CMake\(aqs chosen design will be covered.  Later
sections cover alternative designs that were not chosen for CMake\(aqs
implementation.
.sp
Overall, the designs fall somewhere along two axes:
.TS
box center;
l|l|l.
T{
Explicit Dynamic
T}	T{
Explicit Static
T}	T{
Explicit Fixed
T}
_
T{
Implicit Dynamic
T}	T{
Implicit Static
T}	T{
Implicit Fixed
T}
.TE
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBExplicit\fP builds control which modules are visible to each translation
unit directly.  For example, when compiling a source requiring a module
\fBM\fP, the compiler will be given information which states the exact BMI
file to use when importing the \fBM\fP module.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBImplicit\fP builds can control module visibility as well, but do so by
instead grouping BMIs into directories which are then searched
for files to satisfy \fBimport\fP statements in the source file.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBStatic\fP builds use a static set of build commands in order to complete
the build.  There must be support to add edges between nodes at build time.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBDynamic\fP builds may create new build commands during the build and
schedule any discovered work during the build.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBFixed\fP builds are generated with all module dependencies already known.
.UNINDENT
.SS Design Goals
.sp
CMake\(aqs implementation of building C++ modules focuses on the following design
goals:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
Correct Builds
.IP 2. 3
Deterministic Builds
.IP 3. 3
Support Generated Sources
.IP 4. 3
Static Communication
.IP 5. 3
Minimize Regeneration
.UNINDENT
.SS Correct Builds
.sp
Above all else, an incorrect build is a frustrating experience for all
involved.  A build which does not detect errors and instead lets a build with
detectable problems run to completion is a good way to start wild goose chase
debugging sessions.  CMake errs on the side of avoiding such situations.
.SS Deterministic Builds
.sp
Given an on\-disk state of a build, it should be possible to determine what
steps will happen next.  This does not mean that the exact order of rules
within the build that can be run concurrently is deterministic, but instead
that the set of work to be done and its results are deterministic.  For
example, if there is no dependency between tasks \fBA\fP and \fBB\fP, \fBA\fP should
have no effects on the execution of \fBB\fP and vice versa.
.SS Support Generated Sources
.sp
Code generation is prevalent in the C++ ecosystem, so only supporting modules
in files whose content is known at configure time is not suitable.  Without
supporting generated sources which use or provide modules, code generation
tools are effectively cut off from the use of modules, and any dependencies of
generated sources must also provide non\-modular ways of using their interfaces
(i.e., provide headers).  Given that all C++ implementations use strong
module ownership for symbol mangling, this is problematic when such
interfaces end up referring to compiled symbols in other libraries.
.SS Static Communication
.sp
All communication between different steps of the build should be handled
statically.  Given the build tools that CMake supports,
it is challenging to establish a controlled lifetime for a companion tool that
needs to interact during compilation.  Neither \fBmake\fP nor \fBninja\fP offer a
way to start a tool at the beginning of a build and ensure it is stopped at
the end.  Instead, communication with compilers is managed through input and
output files, using dependencies in the build tool to keep everything
up\-to\-date.  This approach enables standard debugging strategies for builds
and allows developers to run build commands directly when investigating
issues, without needing to account for other tools running in the background.
.SS Minimize Regeneration
.sp
Active development of a build with modules should not require the build graph
to be regenerated on every change.  This means that the module dependencies
must be constructed after the build graph is available.  Without this, a
correct build would need to regenerate the
build graph any time a module\-aware source file is edited, as any changes may
alter module dependencies.
.sp
It also means that all module\-aware sources must be known at configure time
(even if they do not yet exist) so that the build graph can include the
commands to scan for their dependencies.
.sp
\fBNote:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
There is a known issue with \fBninja\fP which can result in an erroneous
detection of a dependency cycle when the dependency order between two
sources reverses (i.e., \fBa\fP importing \fBb\fP becomes \fBb\fP importing
\fBa\fP) between two builds.  See ninja issue 2666 \%<https://\:github\:.com/\:ninja-build/\:ninja/\:issues/\:2666> for details.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Use Case Considerations
.sp
The design goals described above constrain the implementation.  Additionally,
mixed configurations are supported by CMake via multi\-config generators such
as \fBNinja Multi\-Config\fP \%<#\:generator:Ninja Multi-Config> and Visual Studio Generators \%<#\:visual-studio-generators>\&.  This
section describes how CMake addresses these constraints.
.SS Selected Design
.sp
The general strategy CMake uses is to \(dqscan\(dq sources to extract the
ordering dependency information and update the build graph with new edges
between existing edges.  This is done by taking the per\-source scan results
(represented by P1689R5 \%<https://\:www\:.open-std\:.org/\:jtc1/\:sc22/\:wg21/\:docs/\:papers/\:2022/\:p1689r5\:.html> files) and then \(dqcollating\(dq them
for each target with information from its dependencies.  The primary task of
the collator is to generate \(dqmodule map\(dq files to pass to each compile
rule with the paths to the BMIs needed to satisfy \fBimport\fP
statements, and to inform the build tool of dependencies needed to
satisfy those \fBimport\fP statements during the compilation.  The collator also
uses the build\-time information to generate \fBinstall\fP rules for the module
interface units, their BMIs, and properties for any exported
targets with C++ modules.  It also enforces that \fBPRIVATE\fP modules may not
be used by other targets or by any \fBPUBLIC\fP module interface unit
within the target.
.SS Implementation Details
.sp
\fBWarning:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
The implementation details are not a stable interface.  Each version
of CMake may revise them without any attempt at providing compatibility.
External toolchain maintainers are responsible for updating their
implementations for each version of CMake they support.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
This section describes how CMake actually structures the build graph, the data
passed between various parts, and the files which contain that data.  It is
intended to be used both as functional documentation and as a guide to help
those debugging a module build to understand where to locate various bits of
data.
.sp
\fBNote:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
This section documents internal implementation details that may be useful
for \fBtoolchain file\fP \%<#\:manual:cmake-toolchains(7)> authors or during
debugging of a module\-related issue.  Projects should not need to inspect
or modify any of the variables, properties, files, or targets mentioned
here.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Toolchain (scanning)
.sp
Compilers which support modules must also provide a scanning tool.  This will
usually be either the compiler itself with some extra flags or a tool shipped
with the compiler.  The command template for scanning is stored in the
\fBCMAKE_CXX_SCANDEP_SOURCE\fP variable.  The command is expected to write
P1689R5 \%<https://\:www\:.open-std\:.org/\:jtc1/\:sc22/\:wg21/\:docs/\:papers/\:2022/\:p1689r5\:.html> results to the \fB<DYNDEP_FILE>\fP placeholder.  Additionally, the
command should provide any discovered dependencies to the
\fB<DEP_FILE>\fP placeholder.  This allows build tools to
rerun the scan if any of the dependencies of the scanning command change.
.sp
Additionally, toolchains should set the following variables:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCMAKE_CXX_MODULE_MAP_FORMAT\fP: The format of the module map
describing where dependent BMI files for imported modules exist
during compilation.  Must be one of \fBgcc\fP, \fBclang\fP, or \fBmsvc\fP\&.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCMAKE_CXX_MODULE_MAP_FLAG\fP: The arguments used to inform the compiler of
the module map file.  It should use the \fB<MODULE_MAP_FILE>\fP
placeholder.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCMAKE_CXX_COMPILE_BMI\fP: The command template to compile a BMI
file from a module interface unit\&.  Used when
\fBCMAKE_CXX_MODULE_BMI_ONLY_FLAG\fP is not completely additive to an
object compilation template.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCMAKE_CXX_MODULE_BMI_ONLY_FLAG\fP: The arguments used to compile only a
BMI file from a module interface unit\&.  This is used when
consuming modules from external projects to compile BMI files for
use within the current build.
.UNINDENT
.sp
If a toolchain does not provide the \fBCMAKE_CXX_COMPILE_BMI\fP or
\fBCMAKE_CXX_MODULE_BMI_ONLY_FLAG\fP variables, it will not be able to consume
modules provided by \fBIMPORTED\fP targets.
.SS Configure
.sp
During the configure step, CMake needs to track which sources care about
modules at all.  See Scanning Control for
how each source determines whether it cares about modules or not.  CMake
tracks these in its internal target representation structure (\fBcmTarget\fP).
The set of sources which need to be scanned may be modified using the
\fBtarget_sources()\fP \%<#\:command:target_sources>, \fBtarget_compile_features()\fP \%<#\:command:target_compile_features>, and
\fBset_property()\fP \%<#\:command:set_property> commands.
.sp
Additionally, targets may use the \fBCXX_MODULE_STD\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:CXX_MODULE_STD> target property
to indicate that \fBimport std\fP is desired within the target\(aqs sources.
.SS Generate
.sp
During generation, CMake needs to add additional rules to ensure that the
sources providing modules can be built before sources that import those
modules.  Since CMake uses a static build, the build graph must
contain all possible commands for scanning and module generation.  The
dependency edges between commands to ensure that modules are provided will
then ensure that the build graph executes correctly.  This means that, while
all sources may get scanned, only modules that are actually used will be
generated.
.sp
The first step CMake performs is to generate any
synthetic targets needed for a module\-providing
target.  These targets are based on the module provider, but produce only
BMI files for consumers rather than object files. This is necessary
because the compatibility of BMI files is extremely narrow and cannot be
shared between arbitrary \fBimport\fP instances.
.sp
Due to the internal workings of toolchains, there can generally only be a single
set of settings for a variety of flags for any one compilation, including
BMI files for imported modules.  As an example, the C++ standard in
use needs to be consistent across all modules imported to a given translation
unit, mixing standards will cause incompatibilities.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Added in version 4.4: Prior to CMake 4.4, CMake assumed all usages were compatible and would only
create one set of BMIs for each module\-providing target. This
could cause build failures due to incompatible BMI usage.
.sp
In CMake 4.4 and later, CMake attempts to determine BMI
compatibility on a target\-by\-target basis and will generate
synthetic targets to provide compatible
BMIs for consumers.

.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The generated synthetic target has a mix of properties from both
the provider of the module and the consumer. \fBCOMPILE_FEATURES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:COMPILE_FEATURES> and
\fBCOMPILE_OPTIONS\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:COMPILE_OPTIONS> are adopted from the consumer, while all other
relevant properties are inherited from the provider.
.sp
Once all of the synthetic targets are created,
CMake looks at each target that has any source that might use C++ modules and
creates a command to scan each of them.  This command will output a
P1689R5 \%<https://\:www\:.open-std\:.org/\:jtc1/\:sc22/\:wg21/\:docs/\:papers/\:2022/\:p1689r5\:.html>\-formatted file describing the C++ modules it uses and provides (if
any).  It will also create a command to collate module dependencies
for the eligible compilations.  This command depends on the scan
results of all eligible sources, information about the target itself, as well
as the collate results of any dependent targets which provide C++
modules.  The collate step uses a target\-specific
\fBCXXDependInfo.json\fP file which contains the following information:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBcompiler\-*\fP: basic compiler information (\fBid\fP, \fBfrontend\-variant\fP,
and \fBsimulate\-id\fP) which is used to generate correctly formatted paths
when generating paths for the compiler
.IP \(bu 2
\fBcxx\-modules\fP: a map of object files to the \fBFILE_SET\fP information,
which is used to enforce module visibility and generate install
rules for module interface unit sources
.IP \(bu 2
\fBmodule\-dir\fP: where to place BMI files for this target
.IP \(bu 2
\fBdir\-{cur,top}\-{src,bld}\fP: the source (\fBsrc\fP) and build (\fBbld\fP)
directories for the current directory (\fBcur\fP) and the top (\fBtop\fP) of the
project, used to compute accurate relative paths for the build tool
dynamic dependencies
.IP \(bu 2
\fBexports\fP: The list of exports which both contain the target and are
providing C++ module information, used to provide accurate module properties
on \fBIMPORTED\fP targets from the exported targets.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBbmi\-installation\fP: installation information, used to generate install
scripts for BMI files
.IP \(bu 2
\fBdatabase\-info\fP: information required to generate build database
information if requested by \fBEXPORT_BUILD_DATABASE\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:EXPORT_BUILD_DATABASE>
.IP \(bu 2
\fBsources\fP: list of other source files in the target, used to add to the
build database if requested
.IP \(bu 2
\fBconfig\fP: the configuration for the target, used to set the appropriate
properties in generated export files
.IP \(bu 2
\fBlanguage\fP: the language (e.g., C++ or Fortran) the
collation metadata file is describing
.IP \(bu 2
\fBinclude\-dirs\fP and \fBforward\-modules\-from\-target\-dirs\fP: unused for C++
.UNINDENT
.sp
Each entry in the \fBcxx\-modules\fP map records the following:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBbmi\-only\fP (bool): True if only the BMI, not the source of the BMI, is
available
.IP \(bu 2
\fBcompile\-features\fP (list[string]): \fBcmake\-compile\-features(7)\fP \%<#\:manual:cmake-compile-features(7)> used
to build the object
.IP \(bu 2
\fBcompile\-options\fP (list[string]): compilation options/flags used to build
the object, except for those derived from \fBcompile\-features\fP
.IP \(bu 2
\fBdefinitions\fP (list[string]): preprocessor defines used to build the object
.IP \(bu 2
\fBdestination\fP (string): intended install destination of the source file
.IP \(bu 2
\fBinclude\-directories\fP (list[string]): include directories used to build the
object
.IP \(bu 2
\fBname\fP (string): name of the file set which owns the source file
.IP \(bu 2
\fBrelative\-directory\fP (string): base path relative to which the source file
will be relocated into the install destination
.IP \(bu 2
\fBsource\fP (string): path to the source file
.IP \(bu 2
\fBtype\fP (string): type of the file set which owns the source file
.IP \(bu 2
\fBvisibility\fP (string): visibility of the file set which owns the source file
.UNINDENT
.sp
For each compilation, CMake will also provide a module map which will
be created during the build by the collate command.  How this is
provided to the compiler is specified by the \fBCMAKE_CXX_MODULE_MAP_FORMAT\fP
and \fBCMAKE_CXX_MODULE_MAP_FLAG\fP toolchain variables.
.SS Scan
.sp
The compiler is expected to implement the scan command.  This is
because only the compiler itself can reliably answer preprocessor predicates
like \fB__has_builtin\fP in order to provide accurate module usage information
in the face of arbitrary flags that may be used when compiling sources.
.sp
CMake names these files with the \fB\&.ddi\fP extension, which stands for \(dqdynamic
dependency information\(dq.  These files are in P1689R5 \%<https://\:www\:.open-std\:.org/\:jtc1/\:sc22/\:wg21/\:docs/\:papers/\:2022/\:p1689r5\:.html> format and are used by
the collate command to perform its tasks.
.SS Collate
.sp
The collate command performs the bulk of the work to make C++ modules
work within the build graph.  It consumes the following files as input:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCXXDependInfo.json\fP from the generate step
.IP \(bu 2
\fB\&.ddi\fP files from the scanning results of the target\(aqs
sources
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCXXModules.json\fP files output from eligible dependent targets\(aq
collate commands
.UNINDENT
.sp
It uses the information from these files to generate:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCXX.dd\fP files to inform the build tool of dependencies that exist
between the compilation of a source and the BMI files of the modules
that it imports
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCXXModules.json\fP files for use in collate commands of depending
targets
.IP \(bu 2
\fB*.modmap\fP files for each compilation to find BMI files for
imported modules
.IP \(bu 2
\fBinstall\-cxx\-module\-bmi\-$<CONFIG>.cmake\fP scripts for the installation of
any BMI files (included by the \fBinstall\fP scripts)
.IP \(bu 2
\fBtarget\-*\-$<CONFIG>.cmake\fP export files for any exports of the target to
provide the \fBIMPORTED_CXX_MODULES_<CONFIG>\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:IMPORTED_CXX_MODULES_<CONFIG>> properties
.IP \(bu 2
\fBCXX_build_database.json\fP build database files for the target when
the its \fBEXPORT_BUILD_DATABASE\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:EXPORT_BUILD_DATABASE> property is set
.UNINDENT
.sp
During its processing, it enforces the following guarantees:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
BMI usage is consistent
.IP \(bu 2
module visibility is respected
.UNINDENT
.sp
C++ modules have the rule that only a single module of a given name may
exist within a program.  This is not exactly enforceable with the existence of
private modules, but it is enforceable for public modules.  The enforcement is
done by the collate command.  Part of the \fBCXXModules.json\fP files is
the set of modules that are transitively imported by each module it provides.
When a module is then imported, the collate command ensures that all
modules with a given name agree upon a given BMI file to provide that
module.
.SS Compile
.sp
Compilation uses the module map file generated by the collate
command to find imported modules during compilation.  Because CMake only
provides the locations of modules that are discovered by the scan
command, any modules missed by it will not be provided to the compilation.
.SS Install
.sp
During installation, install scripts which have been written by the
collate command during the build are included so that any BMI
files are installed as needed.  These need to be generated, as it is not
known what the BMI file names will be during CMake\(aqs generation
(because CMake names the BMI files after the module name itself).
These install scripts are included with the \fBOPTIONAL\fP keyword, so an
incomplete build may result in an incomplete installation as well.
.SS Alternative Designs
.sp
There are alternative designs that CMake does not implement.  This section
aims to give a brief overview and to explain why they were not chosen for
CMake\(aqs implementation.
.SS Implicit Builds
.sp
An implicit build performs module builds using compile\-time search paths to
make the implementation of the build simpler.  This is certainly something
that can be made to work.  However, CMake\(aqs goals exclude it as a solution.
.sp
When a build uses search directory management, the compiler is directed to
place module output files into a specified directory.  These directories are
then provided as search paths to any compilation allowed to use the modules
within them.
.sp
This strategy risks running into problems with the
Correct Builds goal.  This stems from the
hazard of stale files being present in the search directories.  Since the
build system is unaware of the actual files being written, it is difficult to
know which files are allowed to be deleted (e.g., using \fBninja \-t cleandead\fP
to remove outputs \fBninja\fP has encountered but are no longer generated).
Removal of intermediate files may also cause the build to become stuck if the
outputs are not known to the build system beyond consumers reporting \(dqusage of
file X\(dq.
.sp
There is also a need to at least do some level of ordering of BMI
generation commands which share an output directory.  Separate directories may
be used to order groups of modules (e.g., one directory per target);
otherwise, modules within the same directory may not assume that other modules
writing to the shared directory will complete first.  If module paths are
grouped accurately according to the module dependency graph, it is a small
step to being an explicit build where the files are directly specified.
.SS Static Scanning
.sp
A fixed build performs a scan while generating the build graph and
includes the necessary dependencies up\-front.  In CMake\(aqs case, it would look
at the source files during the generate phase and add the dependencies
directly to the build graph.  This is more likely to be suitable for a
build system that is also its own build tool where build graph
manipulation can be done cooperatively.
.sp
No matter whether it is integrated or not, this strategy necessitates either a
suitable C++ parser to extract the information in the first place, or toolchain
cooperation to obtain it.  While module dependency information is available to
a simpler C++ parser, dependencies may be hidden behind preprocessor
conditionals that need to be understood in order to be accurate.  Of course,
choosing to not support preprocessor conditionals around \fBimport\fP statements
is also an option, but this may severely limit external library support.
.sp
For CMake, this strategy would mean that any change to a module\-aware source
file may need to trigger regeneration of the build graph.  A benign edit would
at least need to trigger the \fIcheck\fP for changed imports, but may skip
actually regenerating if it is unchanged.  This may be less critical for a
build system which is also its own build tool, but it is a
direct violation of the
Minimize Regeneration goal.
.sp
Additionally, CMake\(aqs
Support Generated Sources goal would be
unsupportable with this strategy.  CMake could defer scanning until the
generated files are available, but those sources cannot be compiled until such
a scan has been performed.  This would mean that there would be some unbounded
(but finite) number of regenerations of the build graph as sources become
available.
.SS Module Mapping Service
.sp
Another strategy is to run a service alongside the build that can act as an
oracle for where to place and discover modules.  The compiler is instructed to
query the service with questions such as \(dqthis source is exporting module X\(dq
and \(dqthis source is importing module Y\(dq and receive the path to either create
or find the BMI, respectively.  In this case, the service dynamically
implements the collation logic.
.sp
Of particular note, this conflicts with the
Deterministic Builds and
Static Communication goals because the
on\-disk state may not match the actual state, and coordinating the lifetime of
the build tool itself with the service is difficult.  The primary
missing feature is some signal when a build session starts and ends so that
such a service can know in what context it is answering requests.  There also
needs to be a way to resume a session and detect when a session is
invalidated.  No build tool that CMake supports today has such
features.
.sp
There are also hazards which conflict with the
Correct Builds goal.  When a module is
imported, the compiler waits for a response before continuing.  However, there
is no guarantee that a (visible) module of that name even exists, so it may
wait indefinitely.  While waiting for a compilation to report that it creates
that module, it may run into a dependency cycle which leaves the compilations
hanging until some resource limit is reached (probably time, or that all
possible providers of the module have not reported a module of that name).
While these compilations are waiting on answers, there is the question of how
they affect the parallelism limits of the build tool in use.  Do
compilations waiting on an answer count towards the limit and block other
compilations from launching to potentially discover the module?  If they do
not, what about other resources that may be held in use by those compilations
(e.g., memory or available file descriptors)?
.SH POSSIBLE FUTURE ENHANCEMENTS
.sp
This section documents possible future enhancements to CMake\(aqs support of C++
modules.  Nothing here is a guarantee of future implementation, and the
ordering is arbitrary.
.SS Batch Scanning
.sp
It is possible to scan all sources within a target at once, which should be
faster when sources share transitive includes.  This does have side effects
for incremental builds, as the update of any source in the target means that
all sources in the target are scanned again.  Given how much faster scanning
can be, it should be negligible to do such \(dqextra\(dq scanning assuming that
unchanged results do not trigger recompilations.
.SS BMI Modification Optimization
.sp
Currently, as with object files, compilers always update a BMI file
even if the contents have not changed.  Because modules increase the potential
scope of \(dqnon\-changes\(dq to cause (conceptually) unnecessary recompilation, it
might be useful to avoid recompilation of module consumers if the BMI
file has not changed.  This might be achieved by wrapping the compilation to
juggle the BMI through a \fBcmake \-E copy_if_different\fP pass with
\fBninja\fP\(aqs \fBrestat = 1\fP feature to avoid recompiling importers if the
BMI file doesn\(aqt actually change.
.SS Easier Source Specification
.sp
The initial implementation of CMake\(aqs module support had used the \(dqjust list
sources; CMake will figure it out\(dq pattern.  However, this ran into issues
related to other metadata requirements.  These were discovered while
implementing CMake support beyond just building the modules\-using code.
.sp
Conflicts with Separate BMI Generation on a
single target, as that requires knowledge of all BMI\-generating rules
at generate time.
.SS Separate BMI Generation
.sp
CMake currently uses a single rule to generate both the BMI and the
object file for a compilation.  At least Clang supports compiling an object
directly from the BMI\&.  This would be beneficial because BMI
generation is typically faster than compilation and generating the BMI
as a separate step allows importers to start compiling without waiting for the
object to also be generated.
.sp
This is not supported in the current implementation as only Clang supports
generating an object directly from the BMI\&.  Other compilers either do
not support such a two\-phase generation (GCC) or need to start object
compilation from the source again.
.sp
Conflicts with Easier Source Specification
on a single target because CMake must know all BMI\-generating sources
at generate time rather than build time to create the two\-phase rules.
.SH MODULE COMPILATION GLOSSARY
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B BMI
Built Module Interface.  A compiler\-generated binary representation of a
C++ module\(aqs interface that is required by consumers of the module.  File
extensions vary by compiler.
.TP
.B CMI
Compiled Module Interface.  Alternative name for BMI used by some
compilers.
.TP
.B build database
A JSON file containing compilation commands, module dependencies, and
grouping information.  Used for IDE integration and build analysis.
.TP
.B build system
A tool that facilitates the building of software which includes a model
of how components of the build relate to each other.  For example, CMake,
Meson, build2, and more.
.TP
.B build tool
A build graph execution tool.  For example, \fIninja\fP and \fImake\fP\&.  Some
build tools are also their own build system\&.
.TP
.B C++ module
A C++20 language feature for describing the API of a piece of software.
Intended as a replacement for headers for this purpose.
.TP
.B collate
The process of aggregating module information from scanned sources to
ensure correct compilation order and to provide metadata for other parts
of the build (e.g., installation or a build database).
.TP
.B discovered dependencies
Dependencies found during the processing of a command that do not need to
be explicitly declared.
.TP
.B dynamic dependencies
Dependencies which require a separate command to detect so that a further
command may have its dependencies satisfied.
.TP
.B embarrassingly parallel
A set of tasks which, due to having minimal dependencies between them,
can be easily divided into many independent tasks that can be executed
concurrently.
.TP
.B explicit build
A build strategy where module dependencies are explicitly specified
rather than discovered.
.TP
.B fixed build
A build strategy where all module dependencies are computed and inserted
directly into the build graph.
.TP
.B header unit
A header file which is used via an \fBimport\fP statement rather than an
\fB#include\fP preprocessor directive.  Implementations may provide support
for treating \fB#include\fP as \fBimport\fP as well.
.TP
.B implementation unit
A C++ translation unit that implements module entities declared
in a module interface unit.
.TP
.B implicit build
A build strategy where module dependencies are discovered by searching
for BMI files during compilation.
.TP
.B internal partition unit
A translation unit which contains a partition name and is not
exported from the primary module interface unit\&.
.TP
.B module interface unit
A translation unit that declares a module\(aqs public interface
using \fBexport module\fP\&.  Such a unit may or may not be also be a
partition unit\&.
.TP
.B module map
A compiler\-specific file mapping module names to BMI locations.
.TP
.B module visibility
CMake\(aqs enforcement of access rules for modules based on their
declaration scope (PUBLIC/PRIVATE).
.TP
.B ODR
One Definition Rule.  The C++ requirement that any entity be defined
exactly once per program.
.TP
.B partition unit
A translation unit which describes a module with a partition name
(i.e., \fImodule MODNAME:PARTITION;\fP).  The partition may or may not use
the \fBexport\fP keyword.  If it does, it is also a
module interface unit; otherwise, it is a
internal partition unit\&.
.TP
.B primary module interface unit
A module interface unit which exports a named module that is not
a partition unit\&.
.TP
.B scan
The process of analyzing a translation unit to discover module
imports and exports.
.TP
.B static build
A build configuration where all compilation rules are determined at
generate time.
.TP
.B strong module ownership
C++ implementations have settled on a model where the module \(dqowns\(dq the
symbols declared within it.  In practice, this means that the module name
is included into the symbol mangling of entities declared within it.
.TP
.B synthetic target
A CMake\-generated build target used to supply BMIs to a
specific user of a module\-providing target.
.TP
.B translation unit
The smallest component of a compilation for a C++ program.  Generally,
there is one translation unit per source file.  C++ source files which do
not use C++ modules may be combined into a single translation unit.
.UNINDENT
